answers.body_markdown:
## `Atomic…`

As mentioned in the correct [Answer by Mark Rotteveel][1], an alternative to using `synchronized`/`volatile` is the use of the `Atomic…` classes. 

I prefer the `Atomic…` approach because it makes very clear to the reader *what* resources you are concerned about protecting from multi-threaded access/manipulation. And using `Atomic…` makes quite clear *how* you intend to protect those resources. 

Furthermore, using `Atomic…` often simplifies the code and the reader’s comprehension.

## Properly shutting down executor service

That same Answer by Mark Rotteveel is also correct in pointing out that your code does not properly shut down the executor service. To do so properly, either:

 - Use the boilerplate code in `shutdownAndAwaitTermination` method given on the Javadoc of `ExecutorService`, or…
 - Use [try-with-resources][2] syntax to automatically close the executor service after it completes its tasks (within a day).

I prefer the second approach, try-with-resources.

## Example code

Let&#39;s use both these concepts (`Atomic…` &amp; auto-closing of executor service) in this revised code.

```java
import java.util.Locale;
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;

public class ClientTest
{
    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {
        final AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger ( );

        try (
                ExecutorService executorService = Executors.newFixedThreadPool ( 2 ) ;
        )
        {
            Runnable task1 = ( ) -&gt; {
                for ( int i = 1 ; i &lt;= 20_000 ; i++ )
                {
                    counter.incrementAndGet ( );
                }
            };

            Runnable task2 = ( ) -&gt; {
                for ( int i = 1 ; i &lt;= 80_000 ; i++ )
                {
                    counter.incrementAndGet ( );
                }
            };

            executorService.submit ( task1 );
            executorService.submit ( task2 );
        }
        System.out.println ( &quot;Final counter value: %,d&quot;.formatted ( counter.get ( ) ) );
    }
}
```

&gt;Final counter value: 100,000

I am concerned about our `AtomicInteger` named `counter` here being a local variable. I am not sure if being a local variable presents a visibility problem. I always use the `Atomic…` variables as a `final` instance member (or `static`) variable that is populated on its declaration line as a simple way to ensure thread-safety. 


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/77506903/642706
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html

