&lt;h2&gt;String#format&lt;/h2&gt;

The most frequent way to format a String is using this static method, that is long available since Java 5 and has two overloaded methods:

- [`String#format(String format, Object args...)`][1]
- [`String#format(Locale l, String format, Object args...)`][2]

The method is easy to use and the `format` pattern is defined by underlying [formatter][3].

```
String step1 = &quot;one&quot;;
String step2 = &quot;two&quot;;

// results in &quot;Step one of two&quot;
String string = String.format(&quot;Step %s of %s&quot;, step1, step2); 
```

You can pass a `Locale` to respect the language and regional specification. Refer to this answer for more information: https://stackoverflow.com/a/6431949/3764965 (credits to [Martin T&#246;rnwall][4]).

&lt;h2&gt;MessageFormat&lt;/h2&gt;

The [`MessageFormat`][5] class is available since the first version of Java and is suitable for internationalization. In the simplest form, there is a static method for formatting:

- [`MessageFormat#format​(String pattern, Object... arguments)`][6]

```
String step1 = &quot;one&quot;;
String step2 = &quot;two&quot;;

// results in &quot;Step one of two&quot;
String string = MessageFormat.format(&quot;Step {0} of {1}&quot;, step1, step2);
```

Remember `MessageFormat` follows a specific pattern different from `String#format`, refer to its JavaDoc for more details: [MessageFormat - patterns][7].

It is possible to use `Locale`, however, one has to instantiate the object of the class and pass it to the constructor since the static method above uses the default constructor with the default locale. Refer to this answer for more information: https://stackoverflow.com/a/6432100/3764965 (credits to [ataylor][8]).

&lt;h2&gt;Non standard JDK solutions&lt;/h2&gt;

There are plenty of ways to format Strings using external libraries. They add little to no benefit if the libraries are imported solely for the purpose of String formatting. Few examples:
 - Apache Commons: [`StringSubstitutor`][9], examples in its JavaDoc.
 - Cactoos: [`FormattedText`][10], examples [here][11].
 - Interestingly, Guava doesn&#39;t plan to add formatting or templating features: [#1142][12].
 - ... and other custom implementations.

&lt;sup&gt;Feel free to add more, however, I find no reason to further expand this section.&lt;/sup&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Alternative since Java 15&lt;/h2&gt;

There is a new instance method called [`String#formatted(Object... args)`][13] as of Java 15. 

The internal implementation is the same as [`String#format(String format, Object... args)`][14]. 

&gt; Formats using this string as the format string, and the supplied arguments.

    String step1 = &quot;one&quot;;
    String step2 = &quot;two&quot;;

    // results in &quot;Step one of two&quot;
    String string = &quot;Step %s of %s&quot;.formatted(step1, step2);     
    
**Advantage**: The difference is that the method is not `static` and the formatting pattern is *a string itself* from which a new one is created based on the `args`. This allows chaining to build the format itself first.

**Disadvantage**: There is no overloaded method with `Locale`, therefore uses the default one. If you need to use a custom `Locale`, you have to stick with [`String#format(Locale l, String format, Object... args)`][15].


